The paper discusses interference management in communication networks, which falls under the field of information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on heterogeneous networks, which involve different types of cells and devices, indicating a possible fit with the networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of user-pairing and scheduling, which are common techniques in system and control theory (cs.SY). The use of antenna selection and message scheduling suggests a possible fit with multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of different schemes in terms of bit-error-rate and sum rate, indicating a possible fit with the computer communications (cs.COM) sub-category.
